A.B. 485
ASSEMBLY BILL NO. 485–COMMITTEE ON NATURAL RESOURCES
(ON BEHALF OF THE JOINT INTERIM STANDING
COMMITTEE ON NATURAL RESOURCES)
MARCH 24, 2025
____________
Referred to Committee on Natural Resources
SUMMARY—Revises provisions relating to water. (BDR 48-386)
FISCAL NOTE: Effect on Local Government: No.
Effect on the State: Contains Appropriation not included
in Executive Budget.
~
EXPLANATION – Matter in bolded italics is new; matter between brackets [omitted material] is material to be omitted.
AN ACT relating to water; revising provisions governing certain
assessments on water users; making an appropriation to
the Division of Water Resources of the State Department
of Conservation and Natural Resources for various
projects relating to the management of water resources in
this State and for the digitization of records and data of
the Division; and providing other matters properly
relating thereto.
Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 Existing law requires the board of county commissioners of a county to levy a
2 special assessment in an amount necessary to pay the salaries and expenses of well
3 supervisors, assistants of well supervisors and the Well Drillers’ Advisory Board, if
4 fees collected for certain licenses are not sufficient to pay such salaries and
5 expenses. Existing law authorizes the board of county commissioners of a county to
6 pay those salaries and expenses by appropriating money from the general fund of
7 the county, if the amount of a special assessment combined with all other taxes and
8 assessments levied upon a property owner is less than the cost of collecting the
9 special assessment. Existing law further provides that well supervisors and
10 assistants of well supervisors employed by the State Engineer are exempt from
11 certain provisions of existing law governing public officers and employees. (NRS
12 534.040) Sections 1 and 3 of this bill prohibit the use of the money levied from
13 such a special assessment or money appropriated from the general fund of a county
14 to pay the salaries and expenses of a person employed by the State Engineer who is
15 subject to certain provisions of existing law governing public officers and
16 employees.
